.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.MINUTE" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.minute \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.minute
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]minute\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns an integer from 0 to
59 representing the minute component of this time.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]minute\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
Use the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to create a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object with the desired new value.
.PP
For general information and more examples, see
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime.prototype.minute\f[R].
.PP
For \f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R], \f[CR]minute\f[R] can be non\-continuous
due to offset changes.
While much rarer than \f[CR]hour\f[R] changes (because daylight saving
time shifts are usually by whole hours), it can still happen.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using minute
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56.123456789\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.minute); \f[I]// 34\f[R]
.EE
.SS Non\-continuous minute
Typically, \f[CR]minute\f[R] always goes from 0 to 59 and then back to
0, even when passing through a daylight saving time transition.
There\(cqs one particular case where DST has a 30\-minute offset: Lord
Howe Island in Australia, which shifts between +10:30 and +11:00.
In this case, the minute can be non\-continuous.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-10\-03T01:59:00+10:30[Australia/Lord_Howe]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.minute); \f[I]// 59\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = dt.add({ minutes: 1 });
console.log(dt2.minute); \f[I]// 30\f[R]
console.log(dt2.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-10\-03T02:30:00+11:00[Australia/Lord_Howe]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
There\(cqs a second peculiar case where the minute can be
non\-continuous: the standardization of hourly time zones.
In the early 20th century, most countries were using their own time
zones which were often not a whole hour offset from UTC.
For example, Paris used to have an offset of UTC+0:09:21, which was
changed to UTC+0 on March 11, 1911.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq1911\-03\-10T23:59:00+00:09:21[Europe/Paris]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.minute); \f[I]// 59\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = dt.add({ minutes: 1 });
console.log(dt2.minute); \f[I]// 50\f[R]
console.log(dt2.toString()); \f[I]// 1911\-03\-10T23:50:39+00:00[Europe/Paris]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For this reason, you should always prefer \f[CR]add()\f[R] and
\f[CR]subtract()\f[R] to manipulate dates and times, rather than
directly changing the \f[CR]minute\f[R] property.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
